<ArticleLayout
  title="Bedside Table Setup: What to Check Before You Buy"
  description="A practical Australian guide to choosing a bedside table setup, including size, height, drawers, lamps, charging, cords, small bedrooms, renters and shared rooms."
  category="Bedroom"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/bedroom.webp"
  imageAlt="A calm bedroom with a practical bedside table, lamp and soft bedding"
>
  <p>
    Bedside tables are often chosen quickly because they match a bed frame, fit a style or
    happen to be available in a pair. But they are used every day, and a poor bedside setup
    can quietly make the bedroom harder to use.
  </p>
  <p>
    A table that is too tall, too low, too wide or too shallow can block walkways, make lamps
    awkward, leave cords messy or collect clutter. In small Australian bedrooms, rentals and
    apartments, the wrong bedside choice can also interfere with wardrobe doors, rugs,
    ensuite access or bed-making.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide covers what to measure and check before buying bedside tables, bedside
    drawers, narrow units, simple shelves, lamps, charging accessories or compact night-time
    surfaces. For wider bedroom planning, start with the <a href="/categories/bedroom/">Bedroom</a>{" "}
    category and the <a href="/guides/bedroom-storage-ideas-small-australian-rooms/">small bedroom storage guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Our Take</h2>
  <p>
    A good bedside table should support the way the room is used, not just fill the gap
    beside the bed. For most Australian bedrooms, the right setup is one that sits at a
    comfortable height, leaves enough walkway clearance, handles the items used daily and
    keeps cords, lamps and clutter manageable.
  </p>
  <p>
    A larger or more decorative bedside table is not automatically better if it makes the
    room harder to move through or turns into another pile of unsorted items. The useful
    question is not "does it match?" but "does it suit the bed, the room and the person using
    it?"
  </p>

  <h2>Start With What Actually Needs to Sit Beside the Bed</h2>
  <p>
    Before choosing drawers, shelves or surface size, list what genuinely needs to sit beside
    the bed. Common items include a lamp or reading light, phone and charger, glasses, water
    bottle, book or e-reader, watch, jewellery, tissues, remote controls and small personal
    items.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some households also need space for medication, baby monitors, kids' items or
    health-related equipment. Keep this advice practical: follow product instructions and
    professional guidance for health-related items, and make sure anything used every night
    can be reached without turning the bedside area into a crowded surface.
  </p>
  <p>
    Items used every night need easier access than occasional items. Spare cables, old
    receipts, unused skincare, books that are not being read and wardrobe overflow usually do
    not need to live beside the bed. If the bedside table is becoming general bedroom
    overflow, the problem may sit with the wardrobe or room layout rather than the table
    itself.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure Bed Height, Width and Walkway Clearance</h2>
  <p>
    A bedside table should roughly suit the mattress height and the way the person reaches
    from bed. Very low tables can be awkward beside a high mattress, while very tall tables
    can feel bulky or make lamps, glasses and water bottles sit at an uncomfortable level.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure the gap between the bed and wall, bed and wardrobe, or bed and doorway. Then
    measure the walkway beside the bed. Product photos often show generous rooms, but many
    Australian bedrooms have queen or king beds squeezed into tight spaces with sliding robe
    doors, carpet edges, rugs or bedside power points competing for the same area.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check whether drawers can open fully. Also check bedroom doors, ensuite doors, wardrobe
    doors and robe tracks. A table might fit the gap but still make the room awkward if it
    blocks a drawer, power point, wardrobe opening or cleaning path.
  </p>

  <h2>Bedside Table Types and Where They Work Best</h2>
  <p>
    Simple side tables can work well in small rooms because they provide a surface without
    much bulk. The trade-off is limited hidden space. Bedside drawers can reduce visual
    clutter, but they need enough room to open and can become catch-all drawers if there is no
    clear plan.
  </p>
  <p>
    Open shelf bedside units make books and devices easy to reach, but they can look busy if
    every shelf fills up. Narrow bedside tables are often helpful beside larger beds in small
    rooms. Floating-style shelves or wall-mounted options can save floor space, but they may
    need suitable installation and rental approval. If installation is involved, use qualified
    help where appropriate.
  </p>
  <p>
    Bedheads with shelves can help in tight rooms, though they may collect clutter or reduce
    pillow space. Small stools and occasional tables are flexible, but they may lack drawer
    space or stability for lamps and drinks. A tallboy beside the bed can work in some rooms,
    but it can feel too high or bulky for night-time items. For main clothing drawers, see the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-drawers-tallboys-and-dressers-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">bedroom drawers and dressers guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Drawers, Shelves, Open Cubbies and Closed Storage</h2>
  <p>
    Drawers are useful when the surface needs to stay clear. They can hold tissues, glasses
    cases, chargers, small personal items and a book. The risk is that deep drawers can
    swallow small things and become another place for unsorted clutter.
  </p>
  <p>
    Open shelves are easier to see and grab from, but they need regular tidying. Closed
    cupboards can hold larger items, though they may be awkward in narrow rooms if the door
    needs swing clearance. One small drawer may be enough if the top stays clear and the
    wardrobe has a better plan for clothing and accessories.
  </p>
  <p>
    For shared bedrooms, each person may need a different setup. One side may need drawers
    and charging space while the other only needs a lamp and book shelf. If bedside drawers
    are being used for clothes or linen, it may be worth reviewing the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-wardrobe-organisation-what-to-sort-before-buying-storage/">wardrobe organisation guide</a>{" "}
    or the <a href="/guides/under-bed-storage-what-to-measure-before-you-buy/">under-bed storage guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Lamps, Charging, Cords and Power Access</h2>
  <p>
    Check the nearest power point before buying a table, lamp or charging accessory. A lamp
    needs enough surface area and a stable spot. Phone charging needs a tidy location that
    does not leave cords across walkways or under furniture where they are hard to see.
  </p>
  <p>
    Cord holes, back gaps and cable channels may help if they suit the room. Power boards and
    extension cords should be used according to manufacturer instructions. Avoid overloading
    bedside surfaces, drawers, shelves or power boards, and keep water bottles away from
    electrical items.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renters should avoid permanent cable routing or wall changes unless approved. For wall
    lights, installed lighting or any electrical changes, use qualified advice where
    appropriate. Built-in USB or charging features can be convenient, but check product
    instructions and whether they suit the devices actually used.
  </p>

  <h2>Small Bedrooms, Rentals and Shared Rooms</h2>
  <p>
    Small bedrooms may need narrow tables, wall-adjacent surfaces or one shared central
    surface rather than two full bedside units. Queen and king beds can leave very little side
    clearance in apartments and older homes, especially when the room also has robe tracks,
    carpet, rugs or an ensuite door nearby.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renters usually benefit from freestanding options that can move later. Wall-mounted or
    floating-style choices may be useful in some rooms, but they are not always practical in
    rentals. Avoid permanent fixing unless approved, and use qualified help where the product
    or surface requires it.
  </p>
  <p>
    Shared bedrooms do not need identical bedside setups. Matching tables can look neat, but
    different practical needs may matter more. If one person reads and charges devices while
    the other only needs a lamp, the two sides can be different without looking careless.
  </p>

  <h2>What to Keep on Top and What to Keep Hidden</h2>
  <p>
    Keep the top for items used every night: lamp, phone, glasses, water bottle, book,
    tissues or a small tray. Move spare cables, receipts, coins, old packaging and random
    personal items into a drawer or out of the bedroom altogether.
  </p>
  <p>
    Water bottles should sit securely and away from devices. Jewellery, watches and glasses
    may need a small tray so they do not scatter across the surface. Books can live on an
    open shelf if they are not piling up.
  </p>
  <p>
    Medication and health-related items should be stored according to product and
    professional guidance and kept away from children where relevant. A small bin can help if
    tissues or packaging collect beside the bed, but it should not turn the area into a
    dumping spot.
  </p>

  <h2>Materials, Cleaning and Everyday Wear</h2>
  <p>
    Timber-look, laminate, metal, glass, fabric and painted finishes all wear differently.
    Dark finishes may show dust. Glossy surfaces may show fingerprints. Glass can look light
    but may show marks and sound louder when items are placed on it. Fabric drawers can hold
    dust and be harder to wipe.
  </p>
  <p>
    Rattan or textured finishes can look warm but may collect dust in grooves. Water rings,
    lamps, skincare, oils and drink bottles can mark surfaces. Coasters, trays or wipeable
    finishes may help if the table is used heavily every day.
  </p>
  <p>
    Bedside tables should be easy to move or clean around. Carpet can make lightweight tables
    less steady, while tiled or timber-look floors can make some pieces slide more easily.
    Check how the table feels on the flooring in the room, not just how it looks in a photo.
  </p>

  <h2>Bedside Setup for Guest Rooms and Kids' Rooms</h2>
  <p>
    Guest rooms usually need less than main bedrooms. A lamp, small surface, tissues, charger
    access and a shelf or drawer may be enough. Avoid filling guest bedside tables with
    household overflow, old cables or items that should be stored elsewhere.
  </p>
  <p>
    Kids' rooms may need simpler surfaces, fewer loose items and sturdier furniture. Teen
    rooms may need charging space and a drawer for small personal items. Keep the setup easy
    to reset rather than creating a complicated system that is hard to maintain.
  </p>
  <p>
    Spare rooms that double as offices or storage rooms still need bedside access if guests
    use them. A room does not need hotel-style styling, but it should leave enough room for a
    lamp, glasses, phone and small personal items.
  </p>

  <h2>Trade-Offs Worth Knowing</h2>
  <p>
    Matching bedside tables look tidy, but each side of the bed may have different practical
    needs. More drawers hide clutter, but they can also collect it. Open shelves make items
    easy to grab, but they can look busy. A narrow table saves walkway space, but surface
    area is limited.
  </p>
  <p>
    A large table provides more room but can reduce movement beside the bed. Floating-style
    options free floor space, but installation and rental limits matter. Built-in charging
    can be convenient, but it adds product complexity. Glass and metal surfaces can look
    clean but may show marks or sound noisier in daily use.
  </p>
  <p>
    Decorative styling is pleasant, but daily function matters more. The right bedside setup
    depends on the bed, room, power access, clutter habits and the person using it.
  </p>

  <h2>Before You Buy Checklist</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>List what actually needs to sit beside the bed.</li>
    <li>Measure mattress height.</li>
    <li>Measure the gap beside the bed.</li>
    <li>Check walkway clearance.</li>
    <li>Check whether drawers or doors can open.</li>
    <li>Check wardrobe, bedroom and ensuite door swing or sliding-door access.</li>
    <li>Check power point location before choosing lamps or charging features.</li>
    <li>Decide whether you need drawers, shelves, open cubbies or just a surface.</li>
    <li>Check whether the table height suits the bed.</li>
    <li>Check whether the surface can hold a lamp, phone and night-time items.</li>
    <li>Keep water away from electrical items.</li>
    <li>Avoid creating cord trip points.</li>
    <li>Check product dimensions, weight limits and manufacturer instructions.</li>
    <li>Avoid permanent wall-mounted options in rentals unless approved.</li>
    <li>Choose materials that suit cleaning habits and everyday use.</li>
    <li>Do not buy based only on matching the bed frame.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Buying a bedside table that is too tall or too low.</li>
    <li>Forgetting walkway clearance.</li>
    <li>Choosing drawers that cannot open fully.</li>
    <li>Blocking power points.</li>
    <li>Buying a table too small for a lamp.</li>
    <li>Letting the top become a clutter pile.</li>
    <li>Choosing open shelves when you prefer hidden clutter.</li>
    <li>Buying matching tables when each side of the bed has different needs.</li>
    <li>Using a bedside table as overflow for wardrobe or linen problems.</li>
    <li>Ignoring cords and charging.</li>
    <li>Choosing fragile finishes for heavy everyday use.</li>
    <li>Adding wall-mounted options without considering installation and rental limits.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Suitability-Based Product Angles</h2>
  <p>
    For small bedrooms, narrow bedside tables or compact open shelves may be worth
    considering if walkway clearance is tight. For renters, freestanding bedside tables are
    usually simpler than wall-mounted options. For shared bedrooms, different bedside setups
    may work better than a matching pair.
  </p>
  <p>
    For charging and devices, cord access, stable surfaces and sensible power placement
    matter more than extra drawers. For guest rooms, a simple table with a lamp, surface and
    small shelf may be enough. For closed storage, drawers can reduce visible clutter, but
    only if they are not treated as junk drawers.
  </p>
  <p>
    For narrow spaces, check both table width and drawer-opening clearance before buying. For
    readers, lamp position, book space and surface height should be checked together. For
    warm bedrooms, avoid overcrowding the bedside area if airflow and easy cleaning matter.
  </p>

  <h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
  <p>
    A bedside table setup works best when it is measured around the bed, the room and the
    person using it. The right choice does not need to be large or decorative. It needs to be
    the right height, leave room to move, hold the items actually used at night and keep
    lighting and cords manageable.
  </p>
  <p>
    A simple bedside setup that stays clear and easy to use will usually serve the room
    better than a bulky table chosen only because it matches the bed. Start with what needs
    to live beside the bed, then choose the smallest practical setup that supports that
    routine.
  </p>

